Using the extended Sine law, we find the circumradius of $ABC$ to be $R = \frac{BC}{2\sin A} = 4\sqrt 2$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.8 cm);

pair A, B, C, O, P;

A = (0,0);
B = (2,2);
C = (5,0);
P = interp(B,C,3/8);
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(circumcircle(A,B,C));
draw(O--P);

label("$A$", A, W);
label("$B$", B, N);
label("$C$", C, E);
dot("$O$", O, S);
dot("$P$", P, NE);
[/asy]

By considering the power of point $P$, we find that $R^2 - OP^2 = PB \cdot PC = 15$. So $OP = \sqrt{R^2 - 15} = \sqrt{ 16 \cdot 2 - 15} = \boxed{\sqrt{17}}$.
#### \sqrt{17}

Note that
\[\mathbf{A}^2 = \begin{pmatrix} 15 & 25 \\ -9 & -15 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 15 & 25 \\ -9 & -15 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} = \mathbf{0}.\]Therefore, $\mathbf{A}^n = \mathbf{0}$ for all $n \ge 2,$ which means
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{I} + 2 \mathbf{A} + 3 \mathbf{A}^2 + 4 \mathbf{A}^3 + \dotsb &= \mathbf{I} + 2 \mathbf{A} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} + 2 \begin{pmatrix} 15 & 25 \\ -9 & -15 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 31 & 50 \\ -18 & -29 \end{pmatrix}}.
\end{align*}
#### \begin{pmatrix} 31 & 50 \\ -18 & -29 \end{pmatrix}

Expanding, we get
\begin{align*}
(2 \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (3 \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{a}) &= 6 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + 2 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{a} - 3 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{a} \\
&= 6 \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} - 2 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} - 3 \mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{0} \\
&= 6 \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ - 7 \\ 18 \end{pmatrix} - 2 \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ - 7 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} - 3 \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \\
